<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<h4 style="font-weight:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 1.5in;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:right;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.5in;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Exhibit&nbsp;32.2</font></b></h4>

<h4 style="font-weight:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 1.5in;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:right;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></h4>

<h2 style="font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Certification
Pursuant To</font></b></h2>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-autospace:none;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">18 U.S.C. Section&nbsp;1350</font></b></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-autospace:none;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">As Adopted Pursuant To</font></b></p>

<h2 style="font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Section&nbsp;906
of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002</font></b></h2>

<h2 style="font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></b></h2>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In connection with the Quarterly Report of Abbott Laboratories (the &#147;Company&#148;)
on Form&nbsp;10-Q for the period ended June&nbsp;30, 2009 as filed with the
Securities and Exchange Commission (the &#147;Report&#148;), I, Thomas C. Freyman,
Executive Vice President, Finance and Chief Financial Officer of the Company,
certify, pursuant to 18 U.S.C. &#167; 1350, as adopted pursuant to &#167; 906 of the
Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002, that:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(1)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="2" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Report
fully complies with the requirements of section 13(a)&nbsp;or 15(d)&nbsp;of the
Securities Exchange Act of 1934; and</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(2)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="2" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The information
contained in the Report fairly presents, in all material respects, the
financial condition and results of operations of the Company.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 1.8pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 1 &amp;#151; Basis of
Presentation&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 1.8pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 9.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;The accompanying
unaudited, condensed consolidated financial statements have been prepared
pursuant to rules&amp;nbsp;and regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission
and, therefore, do not include all information and footnote disclosures normally
included in audited financial statements.&amp;nbsp; However, in the opinion of
management, all adjustments (which include only normal adjustments) necessary to
present fairly the results of operations, financial position and cash flows have
been made.&amp;nbsp; It is suggested that these statements be read in conjunction
with the financial statements included in Abbott&amp;#146;s Annual Report on
Form&amp;nbsp;10-K for the year ended December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008.&amp;nbsp; Events that
occurred after June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 through the date that these financial
statements have been filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission were
considered in the preparation of these financial statements.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 9.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;On January&amp;nbsp;1, 2009,
Abbott adopted SFAS No.&amp;nbsp;160 &amp;#147;&lt;EM&gt;&lt;I&gt;&lt;FONT style="FONT-STYLE: normal"
face="Times New Roman"&gt;Noncontrolling Interests in Consolidated Financial
Statements&amp;#151;an amendment of ARB No.&amp;nbsp;51&amp;#148; and accordingly, noncontrolling
interests in subsidiaries are presented as a component of total equity as of
June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31,
2008.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/I&gt;&lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BODY&gt;&lt;/HTML&gt;
</us-gaap:OrganizationConsolidationAndPresentationOfFinancialStatementsDisclosureTextBlock>
  <us-gaap:OtherIncomeAndOtherExpenseDisclosureTextBlock contextRef="D2009Q2YTD">&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN"&gt;
&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;
&lt;META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8"&gt;
&lt;META content="MSHTML 6.00.6000.16850" name=GENERATOR&gt;&lt;/HEAD&gt;
&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 62.3pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 2 &amp;#151; Supplemental
Financial Information&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 62.3pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Other (income) expense,
net, for the first six months of 2009 includes the derecognition of a contingent
liability of $797 million associated with the conclusion of the TAP joint
venture as discussed in Note 9 and income from the recording of certain
investments at fair value in connection with business acquisitions.&amp;nbsp; Other
(income) expense, net, for the second quarter and first six months of 2009 and
2008 includes ongoing contractual payments from Takeda associated with the
conclusion of the TAP joint venture.&amp;nbsp; In connection with the dissolution of
the TAP Pharmaceutical Products Inc. joint venture, Abbott recorded a gain of
approximately $95 million in the second quarter 2008, which is included in Other
(income) expense, net.&amp;nbsp; Other (income) expense, net for the second quarter
and six months ended June&amp;nbsp;30, 2008 also includes a gain of approximately
$52 million on the sale of an equity investment accounted for as an
available-for-sale investment.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Supplemental Cash Flow
Information &amp;#151; Other, net in Net cash from operating activities for 2009 and 2008
includes the effects of contributions to the main domestic defined benefit plan
of $700 million and $200 million, respectively, and to the post-employment
medical and dental plans of $13 million and $65 million in 2009 and 2008,
respectively.&amp;nbsp; Purchases of other investment securities, net in 2009 and
2008 reflects the acquisition of short-term investments with original maturities
of over three months.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;The components of
long-term investments as of June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008 are as
follows:&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 62.3pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;TABLE style="WIDTH: 86.66%; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0
cellPadding=0 width="86%" border=0&gt;
  &lt;TBODY&gt;
  &lt;TR&gt;
    &lt;TD
    style="PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 65.4%; PADDING-TOP: 0in"

  <us-gaap:IncomeTaxDisclosureTextBlock contextRef="D2009Q2YTD">&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN"&gt;
&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;
&lt;META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8"&gt;
&lt;META content="MSHTML 6.00.6000.16850" name=GENERATOR&gt;&lt;/HEAD&gt;
&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 62.3pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 3 &amp;#151; Taxes on
Earnings&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 62.3pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Taxes on earnings reflect
the estimated annual effective rates and include charges for interest and
penalties.&amp;nbsp; The effective tax rates are less than the statutory U.S.
federal income tax rate principally due to the benefit of lower statutory tax
rates and tax exemptions in several foreign taxing jurisdictions.&amp;nbsp; In the
second quarter of 2008, Abbott&amp;#146;s federal income tax returns for 2004 and 2005
were settled, resulting in a net reduction of income taxes of approximately $30
million.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BODY&gt;&lt;/HTML&gt;
</us-gaap:IncomeTaxDisclosureTextBlock>
  <us-gaap:CommitmentsAndContingenciesDisclosureTextBlock contextRef="D2009Q2YTD">&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN"&gt;
&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;
&lt;META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8"&gt;
&lt;META content="MSHTML 6.00.6000.16850" name=GENERATOR&gt;&lt;/HEAD&gt;
&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 62.3pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 4 &amp;#151; Litigation and
Environmental Matters&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 62.3pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Abbott has been identified as a potentially responsible party for
investigation and cleanup costs at a number of locations in the United States
and Puerto Rico under federal and state remediation laws and is investigating
potential contamination at a number of company-owned locations.&amp;nbsp; Abbott has
recorded an estimated cleanup cost for each site for which management believes
Abbott has a probable loss exposure.&amp;nbsp; No individual site cleanup exposure
is expected to exceed $3&amp;nbsp;million, and the aggregate cleanup exposure is not
expected to exceed $15&amp;nbsp;million.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
face="Times New Roman" color=black size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;There are a number of
patent disputes with third parties who claim Abbott&amp;#146;s products infringe their
patents.&amp;nbsp; In April&amp;nbsp;2007, New York University (NYU) and
Centocor,&amp;nbsp;Inc. filed a lawsuit in the Eastern District of Texas asserting
that &lt;I&gt;HUMIRA&lt;/I&gt; infringes a patent co-owned by NYU and Centocor.&amp;nbsp; In
June&amp;nbsp;2009, a jury found that Abbott had willfully infringed the patent and
awarded NYU and Centocor approximately $1.67 billion in past compensatory
damages.&amp;nbsp; The award is subject to review by the trial court.&amp;nbsp; Abbott
will ask the trial court to overturn the verdict and/or reduce the damages
award.&amp;nbsp; In the event that the trial court does not overturn the verdict,
Abbott will appeal.&amp;nbsp; Abbott is confident in the merits of its case and
believes that it will prevail on appeal.&amp;nbsp; As a result, no reserves have
been recorded in this case.&amp;nbsp; Abbott&amp;#146;s acquisition of Kos Pharmaceuticals
Inc. resulted in the assumption of various cases and investigations and Abbott
has recorded reserves related to several of those cases and
investigations.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;There are several civil
actions pending brought by individuals or entities that allege generally that
Abbott and numerous pharmaceutical companies reported false or misleading
pricing information relating to the average wholesale price of certain
pharmaceutical products in connection with federal, state and private
reimbursement.&amp;nbsp; Civil actions have also been brought against Abbott, and in
some cases other members of the pharmaceutical industry, by state attorneys
general seeking to recover alleged damages on behalf of state Medicaid
programs.&amp;nbsp; In May&amp;nbsp;2006, Abbott was notified that the U.S. Department
of Justice intervened in a civil whistle-blower lawsuit alleging that Abbott
inflated prices for Medicaid and Medicare reimbursable drugs.&amp;nbsp; Abbott has
settled a few of the cases and recorded reserves for its estimated losses in a
few other cases, however, Abbott is unable to estimate the range or amount of
possible loss for the remaining cases, and no loss reserves have been recorded
for them.&amp;nbsp; Many of the products involved in these cases are Hospira
products.&amp;nbsp; Hospira, Abbott&amp;#146;s former hospital products business, was spun
off to Abbott&amp;#146;s shareholders in 2004.&amp;nbsp; Abbott retained liability for losses
that result from these cases and investigations to the extent any such losses
both relate to the sale of Hospira&amp;#146;s products prior to the spin-off of Hospira
and relate to allegations that were made in such pending and future cases and
investigations that were the same as allegations existing at the date of the
spin-off.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;There are several civil
actions pending brought by state attorneys general and private entities alleging
antitrust and unfair competition claims in connection with the sales of
&lt;I&gt;TriCor&lt;/I&gt;. Abbott licenses &lt;I&gt;TriCor&lt;/I&gt; from a third party and the licensor
has also been named as a defendant.&amp;nbsp; Settlements have been reached in all
of these cases except the state attorneys general, however, Abbott is unable to
estimate a reserve and no loss reserve has been recorded for the remaining
&lt;I&gt;TriCor&lt;/I&gt; cases.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Within the next year, legal proceedings may occur that may result in a
change in the estimated reserves recorded by Abbott.&amp;nbsp; For its legal
proceedings and environmental exposures, except as noted above, Abbott estimates
the range of possible loss to be from approximately $205 million to $415
million.&amp;nbsp; The recorded reserve balance at June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 for these
proceedings and exposures was approximately $275 million.&amp;nbsp; These reserves
represent management&amp;#146;s best estimate of probable loss, as defined by Statement
of Financial Accounting Standards No.&amp;nbsp;5 &amp;#147;Accounting for
Contingencies.&amp;#148;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
face="Times New Roman" color=black size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;While it is not feasible to predict the outcome of all such proceedings
and exposures with certainty, management believes that their ultimate
disposition should not have a material adverse effect on Abbott&amp;#146;s financial
position, cash flows, or results of operations, except for the cases and
investigations discussed in the third paragraph and the patent case discussed in
the second paragraph of this footnote, the resolution of which could be material
to cash flows or results of operations.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BODY&gt;&lt;/HTML&gt;
</us-gaap:CommitmentsAndContingenciesDisclosureTextBlock>
  <us-gaap:PostemploymentBenefitsDisclosureTextBlock contextRef="D2009Q2YTD">&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN"&gt;

&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.5in 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 5 &amp;#151; Post-Employment
Benefits&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.5in 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Retirement plans consist of defined benefit, defined contribution, and
medical and dental plans.&amp;nbsp; Net cost for the three and six months ended
June&amp;nbsp;30 for Abbott&amp;#146;s major defined benefit plans and post-employment
medical and dental benefit plans is as follows:&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;

&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Abbott funds its domestic defined benefit plans according to IRS funding
limitations.&amp;nbsp; In the first quarters of 2009 and 2008, $700 million and $200
million, respectively, was contributed to the main domestic defined benefit plan
and $13 million and $65 million, respectively, was contributed to the
post-employment medical and dental benefit plans.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BODY&gt;&lt;/HTML&gt;

  <us-gaap:SegmentReportingDisclosureTextBlock contextRef="D2009Q2YTD">&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN"&gt;
&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;
&lt;META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8"&gt;
&lt;META content="MSHTML 6.00.6000.16850" name=GENERATOR&gt;&lt;/HEAD&gt;
&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 7 &amp;#151; Segment
Information&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Abbott&amp;#146;s principal
business is the discovery, development, manufacture and sale of a broad line of
health care products.&amp;nbsp; Abbott&amp;#146;s products are generally sold directly to
retailers, wholesalers, hospitals, health care facilities, laboratories,
physicians&amp;#146; offices and government agencies throughout the world.&amp;nbsp; Abbott&amp;#146;s
reportable segments are as follows:&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;I&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic" face="Times New Roman"
size=2&gt;Pharmaceutical Products&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/I&gt; &amp;#151; Worldwide sales of a broad line of
pharmaceuticals.&amp;nbsp; For segment reporting purposes, two pharmaceutical
divisions are aggregated and reported as the Pharmaceutical Products
segment.&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;I&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic" face="Times New Roman"
size=2&gt;Nutritional Products&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/I&gt; &amp;#151; Worldwide sales of a broad line of
adult and pediatric nutritional products.&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;I&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic" face="Times New Roman"
size=2&gt;Diagnostic Products&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/I&gt; &amp;#151; Worldwide sales of diagnostic systems
and tests for blood banks, hospitals, commercial laboratories and alternate-care
testing sites.&amp;nbsp; For segment reporting purposes, three diagnostic divisions
are aggregated and reported as the Diagnostic Products segment.&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;I&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic" face="Times New Roman"
size=2&gt;Vascular&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/I&gt; &lt;I&gt;Products&lt;/I&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#151; Worldwide sales of coronary,
endovascular, vessel closure and other products.&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Abbott&amp;#146;s underlying
accounting records are maintained on a legal entity basis for government and
public reporting requirements.&amp;nbsp; Segment disclosures are on a performance
basis consistent with internal management reporting.&amp;nbsp; Intersegment
transfers of inventory are recorded at standard cost and are not a measure of
segment operating earnings.&amp;nbsp; The cost of some corporate functions and the
cost of certain employee benefits are charged to segments at predetermined rates
that approximate cost.&amp;nbsp; Remaining costs, if any, are not allocated to
segments. &lt;B&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/B&gt;For acquisitions prior to 2006, substantially all
intangible assets and related amortization are not allocated to
segments.&lt;B&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/B&gt;The following segment information has been prepared in
accordance with the internal accounting policies of Abbott, as described above,
and are not presented in accordance with generally accepted accounting
principles applied to the consolidated financial statements.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;

&lt;/FONT&gt;Approximately 40 to 45 percent of the annual net cost of share-based
awards will typically be recognized in the first quarter due to the timing of
the granting of share-based awards.&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT

derecognition of a contingent liability of $797 established in connection with
the conclusion of the TAP joint venture.&amp;nbsp; Other, net for the three months
and six months ended June&amp;nbsp;30, 2008, includes the gain from the closing of
the TAP joint venture and contractual payments from TAP associated with the
closing of the TAP Pharmaceutical Products Inc. joint venture.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BODY&gt;&lt;/HTML&gt;

&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 8 &amp;#151; Incentive Stock
Program&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 1.45pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;In the first six months of
2009, Abbott granted 1,712,400 stock options, 797,763 replacement stock options,
1,274,400 restricted stock awards and 5,468,552 restricted stock units under
this program.&amp;nbsp; In addition, 2,899,411 options were issued in connection
with the conversion of Advanced Medical Optics,&amp;nbsp;Inc. options to Abbott
options.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; At June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009, approximately 220&amp;nbsp;million
shares were reserved for future grants, including 175 million shares authorized
by Abbott&amp;#146;s shareholders in April&amp;nbsp;2009.&amp;nbsp; Information regarding the
number of options outstanding and exercisable at June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 is as
follows:&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;

&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;

&lt;META content="MSHTML 6.00.6000.16850" name=GENERATOR&gt;&lt;/HEAD&gt;
&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 62.3pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 9 &amp;#151; Conclusion of TAP
Pharmaceutical Products Inc. Joint Venture&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 62.3pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;On April&amp;nbsp;30, 2008,
Abbott and Takeda concluded their TAP Pharmaceutical Products Inc. (TAP) joint
venture, evenly splitting the value and assets of the joint venture.&amp;nbsp;
Abbott exchanged its 50 percent equity interest in TAP for the assets,
liabilities and employees related to TAP&amp;#146;s &lt;I&gt;Lupron&lt;/I&gt; business.&amp;nbsp;
Beginning on May&amp;nbsp;1, 2008, Abbott began recording U.S. &lt;I&gt;Lupron&lt;/I&gt; net
sales and costs in its operating results and no longer records income from the
TAP joint venture.&amp;nbsp; Abbott receives payments based on specified
development, approval and commercial events being achieved with respect to
products retained by Takeda and payments from Takeda based on sales of products
retained by Takeda, which are recorded by Abbott as Other (income) expense, net
as earned.&amp;nbsp; Abbott also agreed to remit cash to Takeda if certain research
and development events were not achieved on the development assets retained by
Takeda.&amp;nbsp; These amounts were recorded as a liability at closing in the
amount of approximately $1.1 billion.&amp;nbsp; Of the $1.1 billion, Abbott made
tax-deductible payments of $83 million and $200 million in 2009 and 2008,
respectively, and Abbott will make a tax-deductible payment of approximately $36
million in 2010.&amp;nbsp; In the first quarter of 2009, events occurred resulting
in certain payments not being required and a liability in the amount of $797
million was derecognized and recorded as income in Other (income) expense,
net.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;The 50 percent-owned joint
venture was accounted for under the equity method of accounting.&amp;nbsp;
Summarized financial information for TAP for the three months and six months
ended June&amp;nbsp;30, 2008 are as follows below: (&lt;I&gt;dollars in
millions&lt;/I&gt;)&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.2in 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;

&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;

&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 10 &amp;#151; Business
Acquisitions&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;In February&amp;nbsp;2009,
Abbott acquired the outstanding shares of Advanced Medical Optics,&amp;nbsp;Inc.
(AMO), a marketer of ophthalmic surgical technology and devices, as well as eye
care solutions for approximately $1.4 billion in cash, net of cash held by
AMO.&amp;nbsp; Prior to the acquisition, Abbott held a small investment in
AMO.&amp;nbsp; Abbott acquired AMO to take advantage of increasing demand for vision
care technologies due to population growth and demographic shifts and AMO&amp;#146;s
premier position in its field.&amp;nbsp; Abbott acquired control of this business on
February&amp;nbsp;25, 2009 and the financial results of the acquired operations are
included in these financial statements beginning on that date in accordance with
Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No.&amp;nbsp;141(R).&amp;nbsp; The
acquisition was financed with long-term debt.&amp;nbsp; The preliminary allocation
of the fair value of the acquisition is shown in the table below &lt;I&gt;(in billions
of dollars)&lt;/I&gt;.&amp;nbsp; These allocations will be finalized when appraisals are
completed.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;

      &lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT

    &lt;TD
    style="BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: windowtext 1pt solid; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 16.06%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double"
    vAlign=bottom width="16%" bgColor=#cceeff&gt;
      &lt;P
      style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: right; punctuation-wrap: simple"
      align=right&gt;&lt;FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman"
      size=2&gt;1.4&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TD&gt;
    &lt;TD
    style="PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 1.48%; PADDING-TOP: 0in"
    vAlign=bottom width="1%" bgColor=#cceeff&gt;
      &lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
      style="FONT-SIZE: 1pt" face="Times New Roman"
  size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TD&gt;&lt;/TR&gt;&lt;/TBODY&gt;&lt;/TABLE&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Acquired intangible assets
consist of established customer relationships, developed technology and trade
names and will be amortized over 2 to 30 years (average of 15 years).&amp;nbsp;
Acquired in-process research and development will be accounted for as an
indefinite lived intangible asset until regulatory approval or
discontinuation.&amp;nbsp; The net tangible assets acquired consist primarily of
trade accounts receivable, inventory, property and equipment and other assets,
net of assumed liabilities, primarily trade accounts payable, accrued
compensation and other liabilities.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Abbott incurred
approximately $70 million of acquisition related expenses in the first six
months of 2009 which are classified as Selling, general and administrative
expense.&amp;nbsp; In addition, subsequent to the acquisition, Abbott repaid
substantially all of the acquired debt of AMO.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;In January&amp;nbsp;2009,
Abbott acquired Ibis Biosciences,&amp;nbsp;Inc. (Ibis) for $175 million, in cash, to
expand Abbott&amp;#146;s position in molecular diagnostics for infectious disease.&amp;nbsp;
Including a $40 million investment in Ibis in 2008, Abbott has acquired 100
percent of the outstanding shares of Ibis.&amp;nbsp; A substantial portion of the
fair value of the acquisition has been allocated to goodwill and amortizable
intangible assets, and acquired in-process research and development which will
be accounted for as an indefinite lived intangible asset until regulatory
approval or discontinuation.&amp;nbsp; The investment in Ibis in 2008 resulted in a
charge to acquired in-process research and development in the first six months
of 2008.&amp;nbsp; In connection with the acquisition, the carrying amount of this
investment was revalued to fair value in the first quarter of 2009 resulting in
recording $33 million of income, which is reported as Other (income) expense,
net.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Had the above acquisitions taken place on January&amp;nbsp;1 of the previous
year, consolidated net sales and income would not have been significantly
different from reported amounts.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BODY&gt;&lt;/HTML&gt;
</us-gaap:BusinessCombinationDisclosureTextBlock>
  <us-gaap:DerivativeInstrumentsAndHedgingActivitiesDisclosureTextBlock contextRef="D2009Q2YTD">&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN"&gt;
&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;
&lt;META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8"&gt;
&lt;META content="MSHTML 6.00.6000.16850" name=GENERATOR&gt;&lt;/HEAD&gt;
&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.5in 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 11 &amp;#151; Financial
Instruments, Derivatives and Fair Value Measures&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.5in 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Certain Abbott foreign
subsidiaries enter into foreign currency forward exchange contracts to manage
exposures to changes in foreign exchange rates for anticipated intercompany
purchases by those subsidiaries whose functional currencies are not the U.S.
dollar.&amp;nbsp; These contracts, totaling $470&lt;B&gt; &lt;/B&gt;million and $129 million at
June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008, respectively, are designated as
cash flow hedges of the variability of the cash flows due to changes in foreign
exchange rates.&lt;B&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/B&gt;Accumulated gains and losses as of June&amp;nbsp;30,
2009 will be included in Cost of products sold at the time the products are
sold, generally through the next twelve months.&amp;nbsp; The amount of hedge
ineffectiveness was not significant in 2009 and 2008 for these
hedges.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Abbott enters into foreign currency forward exchange contracts to manage
currency exposures for foreign currency denominated third-party trade payables
and receivables, and for intercompany loans and trade accounts payable where the
receivable or payable is denominated in a currency other than the functional
currency of the entity.&amp;nbsp; For intercompany loans, the contracts require
Abbott to sell or buy foreign currencies, primarily European currencies and
Japanese yen, in exchange for primarily U.S. dollars and other European
currencies.&amp;nbsp; For intercompany and trade payables and receivables, the
currency exposures are primarily the U.S. dollar, European currencies and
Japanese yen.&amp;nbsp; At June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008, Abbott
held $6.5 billion and $8.3 billion, respectively, of such foreign currency
forward exchange contracts.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
face="Times New Roman" color=black size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Abbott has designated foreign denominated short-term debt as a hedge of
the net investment in certain foreign subsidiaries of approximately $556 million
and approximately $585 million as of June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31,
2008, respectively.&amp;nbsp; Accordingly, changes in the fair value of this debt
due to changes in exchange rates are recorded in Accumulated other comprehensive
income (loss), net of tax.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
face="Times New Roman" color=black size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Abbott is a party to interest rate swap contracts totaling $5.5 billion
and $2.5 billion at June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008, respectively,
to manage its exposure to changes in the fair value of $5.5 billion and $2.5
billion, respectively, of fixed-rate debt due 2011 through 2019.&amp;nbsp; These
contracts are designated as fair value hedges of the variability of the fair
value of fixed-rate debt due to changes in the long-term benchmark interest
rates.&amp;nbsp; The effect of the hedge is to change a fixed-rate interest
obligation to a variable rate for that portion of the debt.&amp;nbsp; Abbott records
the contracts at fair value and adjusts the carrying amount of the fixed-rate
debt by an offsetting amount.&amp;nbsp; No hedge ineffectiveness was recorded in
income in 2009 or 2008 for these hedges.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
face="Times New Roman" color=black size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;The following table
summarizes the amounts and location of certain derivative financial instruments
as of June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008:&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;

      &lt;P
      style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center; punctuation-wrap: simple"

    &lt;TD
    style="BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 7%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 1pt solid"
    vAlign=bottom width="7%" colSpan=2&gt;
      &lt;P
      style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center; punctuation-wrap: simple"
      align=center&gt;&lt;B&gt;&lt;FONT style="FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 8pt"
      face="Times New Roman" size=1&gt;June 30&lt;BR&gt;2009&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TD&gt;
    &lt;TD
    style="PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 2%; PADDING-TOP: 0in"
    vAlign=bottom width="2%"&gt;
      &lt;P

&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: normal; TEXT-ALIGN: left; punctuation-wrap: simple"
align=left&gt;&lt;FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman"
size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: normal; TEXT-ALIGN: left; punctuation-wrap: simple"
align=left&gt;&lt;FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;The
following table summarizes the activity for foreign currency forward exchange
contracts designated as cash flow hedges, debt designated as a hedge of net
investment in certain foreign subsidiaries and the amounts and location of
income (expense) and gain (loss) reclassified into income in the second quarter
and first six months of 2009 and 2008 and for certain other derivative financial
instruments.&amp;nbsp; The amount of hedge ineffectiveness was not significant in
2009 and 2008 for these hedges.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;

&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: normal; TEXT-ALIGN: left; punctuation-wrap: simple"
align=left&gt;&lt;FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;The
carrying values and fair values of certain financial instruments as of
June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008 are shown in the table below. The
carrying values of all other financial instruments approximate their estimated
fair values.&amp;nbsp; The counterparties to financial instruments consist of select
major international financial institutions. Abbott does not expect any losses
from nonperformance by these counterparties.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;

&lt;P

align=left&gt;&lt;FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;The value
of the financial assets and liabilities relating to TAP employees&amp;#146; stock options
are calculated using the Black-Scholes option-pricing model.&amp;nbsp; Changes in
the recorded amounts are recorded in Other income (expense), net each
period.&amp;nbsp; The recorded value of investments that are valued using
significant unobservable inputs did not change significantly.&amp;nbsp; Changes in
these values are recorded in Accumulated other comprehensive
income.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BODY&gt;&lt;/HTML&gt;

  <us-gaap:GoodwillAndIntangibleAssetsDisclosureTextBlock contextRef="D2009Q2YTD">&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN"&gt;
&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;
&lt;META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8"&gt;
&lt;META content="MSHTML 6.00.6000.16850" name=GENERATOR&gt;&lt;/HEAD&gt;
&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt"&gt;Note&amp;nbsp;12&amp;nbsp;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;#151; Goodwill and Intangible
Assets&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Abbott recorded goodwill
of approximately $1.7 billion in 2009 related to the acquisitions of Advanced
Medical Optics,&amp;nbsp;Inc. and Ibis Biosciences,&amp;nbsp;Inc.&amp;nbsp; In connection
with the dissolution of the TAP Pharmaceutical Products Inc. (TAP) joint venture
in 2008, Abbott recorded approximately $350 million of goodwill. Goodwill
related to the Ibis acquisition was allocated to the Diagnostic Products segment
and goodwill related to TAP was allocated to the Pharmaceutical Products
segment.&amp;nbsp; Foreign currency translation adjustments and other adjustments
increased goodwill in the first six months of 2009 and 2008 by approximately
$506&lt;B&gt; &lt;/B&gt;million and $312 million, respectively.&amp;nbsp; The amount of goodwill
related to reportable segments at June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 was $6.3 billion for the
Pharmaceutical Products segment, $206 million for the Nutritional Products
segment, $386 million for the Diagnostic Products segment and $2.4 billion for
the Vascular Products segment.&amp;nbsp; There were no reductions of goodwill
relating to impairments or disposal of all or a portion of a
business.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;The gross amount of
amortizable intangible assets, primarily product rights and technology, was
$10.6 billion&lt;B&gt; &lt;/B&gt;as of June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and $9.4 billion as of
December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008, and accumulated amortization was $4.6 billion as of
June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and $4.2 billion as of December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008.&amp;nbsp; The
estimated annual amortization expense for intangible assets is approximately
$847 million in 2009, $859 million in 2010, $844 million in 2011, $831 million
in 2012 and $675 million in 2013. Amortizable intangible assets are amortized
over 4 to 25&amp;nbsp;years (average 11 years).&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BODY&gt;&lt;/HTML&gt;
</us-gaap:GoodwillAndIntangibleAssetsDisclosureTextBlock>
  <us-gaap:RestructuringAndRelatedActivitiesDisclosureTextBlock contextRef="D2009Q2YTD">&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN"&gt;
&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;
&lt;META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8"&gt;
&lt;META content="MSHTML 6.00.6000.16850" name=GENERATOR&gt;&lt;/HEAD&gt;
&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.5in 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 13 &amp;#151; Restructuring
Plans&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.5in 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;In 2008, Abbott management
approved a plan to streamline global manufacturing operations, reduce overall
costs, and improve efficiencies in Abbott&amp;#146;s core diagnostic business.&amp;nbsp;
Additional charges of approximately $23 million were recorded in the first six
months of 2009 relating to this restructuring, primarily for accelerated
depreciation and product transfer costs.&amp;nbsp; Additional charges will occur
through 2011 as a result of product re-registration timelines required under
manufacturing regulations in a number of countries and product transition
timelines.&amp;nbsp; The following summarizes the activity for this
restructuring:&amp;nbsp; &lt;I&gt;(dollars in millions)&lt;/I&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;I&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic" face="Times New Roman"
size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/I&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;TABLE style="WIDTH: 46.66%; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0
cellPadding=0 width="46%" border=0&gt;
  &lt;TBODY&gt;
  &lt;TR&gt;
    &lt;TD
    style="PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 66.78%; PADDING-TOP: 0in"
    vAlign=bottom width="66%"&gt;
      &lt;P
      style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 10pt; TEXT-INDENT: -10pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;B&gt;&lt;FONT
      style="FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 1pt" face="Times New Roman"

&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;In 2009 and prior years,
Abbott management approved plans to realign its worldwide pharmaceutical and
vascular manufacturing operations and selected domestic and international
commercial and research and development operations in order to reduce
costs.&amp;nbsp; Additional charges of $20 million and $44 million were subsequently
recorded in the first six months of 2009 and 2008, respectively, relating to
these restructurings, primarily for accelerated depreciation and product
transfer costs.&amp;nbsp; The following summarizes the activity for these
restructurings: &lt;I&gt;(dollars in millions)&lt;/I&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;

&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 14 &amp;#151; Subsequent Event
&amp;#151; Litigation Settlement&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; VERTICAL-ALIGN: baseline; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;In July&amp;nbsp;2009, Abbott and Medtronic,&amp;nbsp;Inc. reached a settlement
resolving all outstanding intellectual property litigation between the two
parties.&amp;nbsp; Under the terms of the settlement, Medtronic will pay Abbott $400
million.&amp;nbsp; The settlement also includes a mutual agreement not to pursue
additional litigation on current and future vascular products, subject to
specific conditions and time limits.&amp;nbsp; The one-time impact of this
settlement will be included in third quarter 2009
earnings.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BODY&gt;&lt;/HTML&gt;

&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 7 &amp;#151; Segment
Information&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Abbott&amp;#146;s principal
business is the discovery, development, manufacture and sale of a broad line of
health care products.&amp;nbsp; Abbott&amp;#146;s products are generally sold directly to
retailers, wholesalers, hospitals, health care facilities, laboratories,
physicians&amp;#146; offices and government agencies throughout the world.&amp;nbsp; Abbott&amp;#146;s
reportable segments are as follows:&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;I&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic" face="Times New Roman"
size=2&gt;Pharmaceutical Products&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/I&gt; &amp;#151; Worldwide sales of a broad line of
pharmaceuticals.&amp;nbsp; For segment reporting purposes, two pharmaceutical
divisions are aggregated and reported as the Pharmaceutical Products
segment.&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;I&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic" face="Times New Roman"
size=2&gt;Nutritional Products&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/I&gt; &amp;#151; Worldwide sales of a broad line of
adult and pediatric nutritional products.&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;I&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic" face="Times New Roman"
size=2&gt;Diagnostic Products&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/I&gt; &amp;#151; Worldwide sales of diagnostic systems
and tests for blood banks, hospitals, commercial laboratories and alternate-care
testing sites.&amp;nbsp; For segment reporting purposes, three diagnostic divisions
are aggregated and reported as the Diagnostic Products segment.&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;I&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic" face="Times New Roman"
size=2&gt;Vascular&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/I&gt; &lt;I&gt;Products&lt;/I&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#151; Worldwide sales of coronary,
endovascular, vessel closure and other products.&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Abbott&amp;#146;s underlying
accounting records are maintained on a legal entity basis for government and
public reporting requirements.&amp;nbsp; Segment disclosures are on a performance
basis consistent with internal management reporting.&amp;nbsp; Intersegment
transfers of inventory are recorded at standard cost and are not a measure of
segment operating earnings.&amp;nbsp; The cost of some corporate functions and the
cost of certain employee benefits are charged to segments at predetermined rates
that approximate cost.&amp;nbsp; Remaining costs, if any, are not allocated to
segments. &lt;B&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/B&gt;For acquisitions prior to 2006, substantially all
intangible assets and related amortization are not allocated to
segments.&lt;B&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/B&gt;The following segment information has been prepared in
accordance with the internal accounting policies of Abbott, as described above,
and are not presented in accordance with generally accepted accounting
principles applied to the consolidated financial statements.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT

&lt;HR align=left width="25%" color=black noShade SIZE=1&gt;
&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;P
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;(a)&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 3pt"
size=1&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;
&lt;/FONT&gt;Approximately 40 to 45 percent of the annual net cost of share-based
awards will typically be recognized in the first quarter due to the timing of
the granting of share-based awards.&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;(b)&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 3pt" size=1&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;
&lt;/FONT&gt;Other, net, for the six months ended June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009, includes the
derecognition of a contingent liability of $797 established in connection with
the conclusion of the TAP joint venture.&amp;nbsp; Other, net for the three months
and six months ended June&amp;nbsp;30, 2008, includes the gain from the closing of
the TAP joint venture and contractual payments from TAP associated with the
closing of the TAP Pharmaceutical Products Inc. joint venture.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BODY&gt;&lt;/HTML&gt;

Abbott&amp;#146;s principal
business is the discovery, development, manufacture and sale of a broad line of
health care</NonNumericTextHeader>

          <NonNumbericText>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN"&gt;
&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;
&lt;META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8"&gt;
&lt;META content="MSHTML 6.00.6000.16850" name=GENERATOR&gt;&lt;/HEAD&gt;
&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 62.3pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 4 &amp;#151; Litigation and
Environmental Matters&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 62.3pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Abbott has been identified as a potentially responsible party for
investigation and cleanup costs at a number of locations in the United States
and Puerto Rico under federal and state remediation laws and is investigating
potential contamination at a number of company-owned locations.&amp;nbsp; Abbott has
recorded an estimated cleanup cost for each site for which management believes
Abbott has a probable loss exposure.&amp;nbsp; No individual site cleanup exposure
is expected to exceed $3&amp;nbsp;million, and the aggregate cleanup exposure is not
expected to exceed $15&amp;nbsp;million.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
face="Times New Roman" color=black size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;There are a number of
patent disputes with third parties who claim Abbott&amp;#146;s products infringe their
patents.&amp;nbsp; In April&amp;nbsp;2007, New York University (NYU) and
Centocor,&amp;nbsp;Inc. filed a lawsuit in the Eastern District of Texas asserting
that &lt;I&gt;HUMIRA&lt;/I&gt; infringes a patent co-owned by NYU and Centocor.&amp;nbsp; In
June&amp;nbsp;2009, a jury found that Abbott had willfully infringed the patent and
awarded NYU and Centocor approximately $1.67 billion in past compensatory
damages.&amp;nbsp; The award is subject to review by the trial court.&amp;nbsp; Abbott
will ask the trial court to overturn the verdict and/or reduce the damages
award.&amp;nbsp; In the event that the trial court does not overturn the verdict,
Abbott will appeal.&amp;nbsp; Abbott is confident in the merits of its case and
believes that it will prevail on appeal.&amp;nbsp; As a result, no reserves have
been recorded in this case.&amp;nbsp; Abbott&amp;#146;s acquisition of Kos Pharmaceuticals
Inc. resulted in the assumption of various cases and investigations and Abbott
has recorded reserves related to several of those cases and
investigations.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;There are several civil
actions pending brought by individuals or entities that allege generally that
Abbott and numerous pharmaceutical companies reported false or misleading
pricing information relating to the average wholesale price of certain
pharmaceutical products in connection with federal, state and private
reimbursement.&amp;nbsp; Civil actions have also been brought against Abbott, and in
some cases other members of the pharmaceutical industry, by state attorneys
general seeking to recover alleged damages on behalf of state Medicaid
programs.&amp;nbsp; In May&amp;nbsp;2006, Abbott was notified that the U.S. Department
of Justice intervened in a civil whistle-blower lawsuit alleging that Abbott
inflated prices for Medicaid and Medicare reimbursable drugs.&amp;nbsp; Abbott has
settled a few of the cases and recorded reserves for its estimated losses in a
few other cases, however, Abbott is unable to estimate the range or amount of
possible loss for the remaining cases, and no loss reserves have been recorded
for them.&amp;nbsp; Many of the products involved in these cases are Hospira
products.&amp;nbsp; Hospira, Abbott&amp;#146;s former hospital products business, was spun
off to Abbott&amp;#146;s shareholders in 2004.&amp;nbsp; Abbott retained liability for losses
that result from these cases and investigations to the extent any such losses
both relate to the sale of Hospira&amp;#146;s products prior to the spin-off of Hospira
and relate to allegations that were made in such pending and future cases and
investigations that were the same as allegations existing at the date of the
spin-off.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;There are several civil
actions pending brought by state attorneys general and private entities alleging
antitrust and unfair competition claims in connection with the sales of
&lt;I&gt;TriCor&lt;/I&gt;. Abbott licenses &lt;I&gt;TriCor&lt;/I&gt; from a third party and the licensor
has also been named as a defendant.&amp;nbsp; Settlements have been reached in all
of these cases except the state attorneys general, however, Abbott is unable to
estimate a reserve and no loss reserve has been recorded for the remaining
&lt;I&gt;TriCor&lt;/I&gt; cases.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Within the next year, legal proceedings may occur that may result in a
change in the estimated reserves recorded by Abbott.&amp;nbsp; For its legal
proceedings and environmental exposures, except as noted above, Abbott estimates
the range of possible loss to be from approximately $205 million to $415
million.&amp;nbsp; The recorded reserve balance at June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 for these
proceedings and exposures was approximately $275 million.&amp;nbsp; These reserves
represent management&amp;#146;s best estimate of probable loss, as defined by Statement
of Financial Accounting Standards No.&amp;nbsp;5 &amp;#147;Accounting for
Contingencies.&amp;#148;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
face="Times New Roman" color=black size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;While it is not feasible to predict the outcome of all such proceedings
and exposures with certainty, management believes that their ultimate
disposition should not have a material adverse effect on Abbott&amp;#146;s financial
position, cash flows, or results of operations, except for the cases and
investigations discussed in the third paragraph and the patent case discussed in
the second paragraph of this footnote, the resolution of which could be material
to cash flows or results of operations.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BODY&gt;&lt;/HTML&gt;
</NonNumbericText>
          <NonNumericTextHeader>Note 4 &amp;#151; Litigation and
Environmental Matters
&amp;nbsp;
Abbott has been identified as a potentially responsible party for
investigation and cleanup costs</NonNumericTextHeader>

&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;

&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 10 &amp;#151; Business
Acquisitions&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;In February&amp;nbsp;2009,
Abbott acquired the outstanding shares of Advanced Medical Optics,&amp;nbsp;Inc.
(AMO), a marketer of ophthalmic surgical technology and devices, as well as eye
care solutions for approximately $1.4 billion in cash, net of cash held by
AMO.&amp;nbsp; Prior to the acquisition, Abbott held a small investment in
AMO.&amp;nbsp; Abbott acquired AMO to take advantage of increasing demand for vision
care technologies due to population growth and demographic shifts and AMO&amp;#146;s
premier position in its field.&amp;nbsp; Abbott acquired control of this business on
February&amp;nbsp;25, 2009 and the financial results of the acquired operations are
included in these financial statements beginning on that date in accordance with
Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No.&amp;nbsp;141(R).&amp;nbsp; The
acquisition was financed with long-term debt.&amp;nbsp; The preliminary allocation
of the fair value of the acquisition is shown in the table below &lt;I&gt;(in billions
of dollars)&lt;/I&gt;.&amp;nbsp; These allocations will be finalized when appraisals are
completed.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;

    &lt;TD

    &lt;TD

    vAlign=bottom width="1%" bgColor=#cceeff&gt;
      &lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
      style="FONT-SIZE: 1pt" face="Times New Roman"
  size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TD&gt;&lt;/TR&gt;&lt;/TBODY&gt;&lt;/TABLE&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Acquired intangible assets
consist of established customer relationships, developed technology and trade
names and will be amortized over 2 to 30 years (average of 15 years).&amp;nbsp;
Acquired in-process research and development will be accounted for as an
indefinite lived intangible asset until regulatory approval or
discontinuation.&amp;nbsp; The net tangible assets acquired consist primarily of
trade accounts receivable, inventory, property and equipment and other assets,
net of assumed liabilities, primarily trade accounts payable, accrued
compensation and other liabilities.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Abbott incurred
approximately $70 million of acquisition related expenses in the first six
months of 2009 which are classified as Selling, general and administrative
expense.&amp;nbsp; In addition, subsequent to the acquisition, Abbott repaid
substantially all of the acquired debt of AMO.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;In January&amp;nbsp;2009,
Abbott acquired Ibis Biosciences,&amp;nbsp;Inc. (Ibis) for $175 million, in cash, to
expand Abbott&amp;#146;s position in molecular diagnostics for infectious disease.&amp;nbsp;
Including a $40 million investment in Ibis in 2008, Abbott has acquired 100
percent of the outstanding shares of Ibis.&amp;nbsp; A substantial portion of the
fair value of the acquisition has been allocated to goodwill and amortizable
intangible assets, and acquired in-process research and development which will
be accounted for as an indefinite lived intangible asset until regulatory
approval or discontinuation.&amp;nbsp; The investment in Ibis in 2008 resulted in a
charge to acquired in-process research and development in the first six months
of 2008.&amp;nbsp; In connection with the acquisition, the carrying amount of this
investment was revalued to fair value in the first quarter of 2009 resulting in
recording $33 million of income, which is reported as Other (income) expense,
net.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Had the above acquisitions taken place on January&amp;nbsp;1 of the previous
year, consolidated net sales and income would not have been significantly
different from reported amounts.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BODY&gt;&lt;/HTML&gt;
</NonNumbericText>
          <NonNumericTextHeader>Note 10 &amp;#151; Business
Acquisitions
&amp;nbsp;
In February&amp;nbsp;2009,
Abbott acquired the outstanding shares of Advanced Medical Optics,&amp;nbsp;Inc.
(AMO), a</NonNumericTextHeader>

          <NonNumbericText>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN"&gt;
&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;
&lt;META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8"&gt;
&lt;META content="MSHTML 6.00.6000.16850" name=GENERATOR&gt;&lt;/HEAD&gt;
&lt;BODY&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.5in 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Note 11 &amp;#151; Financial
Instruments, Derivatives and Fair Value Measures&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.5in 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;Certain Abbott foreign
subsidiaries enter into foreign currency forward exchange contracts to manage
exposures to changes in foreign exchange rates for anticipated intercompany
purchases by those subsidiaries whose functional currencies are not the U.S.
dollar.&amp;nbsp; These contracts, totaling $470&lt;B&gt; &lt;/B&gt;million and $129 million at
June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008, respectively, are designated as
cash flow hedges of the variability of the cash flows due to changes in foreign
exchange rates.&lt;B&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/B&gt;Accumulated gains and losses as of June&amp;nbsp;30,
2009 will be included in Cost of products sold at the time the products are
sold, generally through the next twelve months.&amp;nbsp; The amount of hedge
ineffectiveness was not significant in 2009 and 2008 for these
hedges.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0in; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Abbott enters into foreign currency forward exchange contracts to manage
currency exposures for foreign currency denominated third-party trade payables
and receivables, and for intercompany loans and trade accounts payable where the
receivable or payable is denominated in a currency other than the functional
currency of the entity.&amp;nbsp; For intercompany loans, the contracts require
Abbott to sell or buy foreign currencies, primarily European currencies and
Japanese yen, in exchange for primarily U.S. dollars and other European
currencies.&amp;nbsp; For intercompany and trade payables and receivables, the
currency exposures are primarily the U.S. dollar, European currencies and
Japanese yen.&amp;nbsp; At June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008, Abbott
held $6.5 billion and $8.3 billion, respectively, of such foreign currency
forward exchange contracts.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
face="Times New Roman" color=black size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Abbott has designated foreign denominated short-term debt as a hedge of
the net investment in certain foreign subsidiaries of approximately $556 million
and approximately $585 million as of June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31,
2008, respectively.&amp;nbsp; Accordingly, changes in the fair value of this debt
due to changes in exchange rates are recorded in Accumulated other comprehensive
income (loss), net of tax.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
face="Times New Roman" color=black size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: windowtext" face="Times New Roman" color=black
size=2&gt;Abbott is a party to interest rate swap contracts totaling $5.5 billion
and $2.5 billion at June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008, respectively,
to manage its exposure to changes in the fair value of $5.5 billion and $2.5
billion, respectively, of fixed-rate debt due 2011 through 2019.&amp;nbsp; These
contracts are designated as fair value hedges of the variability of the fair
value of fixed-rate debt due to changes in the long-term benchmark interest
rates.&amp;nbsp; The effect of the hedge is to change a fixed-rate interest
obligation to a variable rate for that portion of the debt.&amp;nbsp; Abbott records
the contracts at fair value and adjusts the carrying amount of the fixed-rate
debt by an offsetting amount.&amp;nbsp; No hedge ineffectiveness was recorded in
income in 2009 or 2008 for these hedges.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; COLOR: black; punctuation-wrap: hanging"&gt;&lt;FONT
face="Times New Roman" color=black size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;The following table
summarizes the amounts and location of certain derivative financial instruments
as of June&amp;nbsp;30, 2009 and December&amp;nbsp;31, 2008:&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; punctuation-wrap: simple"&gt;&lt;FONT
style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;

style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: normal; TEXT-ALIGN: left; punctuation-wrap: simple"

&lt;P
style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: normal; TEXT-ALIGN: left; punctuation-wrap: simple"
align=left&gt;&lt;FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt" face="Times New Roman" size=2&gt;The
following table summarizes the activity for foreign currency forward exchange
contracts designated as cash flow hedges, debt designated as a hedge of net
investment in certain foreign subsidiaries and the amounts and location of
income (expense) and gain (loss) reclassified into income in the second quarter
and first six months of 2009 and 2008 and for certain other derivative financial
instruments.&amp;nbsp; The amount of hedge ineffectiveness was not significant in
2009 and 2008 for these hedges.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
